    <strong>Steelcase Conflict<br>of Interest Policy</strong>
  </header>
  <div class="heading vspace">
    <strong>
      <em>Purpose</em>
    </strong>
  </div>
  <p class="vspace wrapper-inner">
    The Steelcase Inc. Conflict of Interest policy is founded on the belief that Temporary Workers shall perform the responsibilities of their position solely on the basis of what is in the best interest of the Company. The Conflict of Interest policy applies to all employees and temporary workers of Steelcase Inc. and its entities and affiliates.
  </p>
  <div class="heading vspace">
    <strong>
      <em>Overview</em>
    </strong>
  </div>
  <p class="vspace wrapper-inner">
    Temporary Workers must set aside personal considerations and relationships when making decisions or recommendations on behalf of the Company. Also, temporary workers should do their best to prevent the company from doing anything illegal or unethical. If a temporary workers has a question about a potential conflict of interest, he or she should contact their Steelcase Manager or the Director of Global Audit Services.
  </p>
  <div class="heading vspace">
    <strong>
      <em>Specifics</em>
    </strong>
  </div>
  <div class="wrapper-inner">
    <p class="vspace">
      <strong><u>Guidelines for Temporary Employees</u></strong>
    </p>
    <p class="vspace">
      As a guideline to completing the personal declaration form, certain practices are identified as presenting a high risk that may result in a conflict of interest. These <strong>PROHIBITED</strong> activities include,
    </p>
    <ul class="vspace">
      <li>
        <strong>Accepting entertainment, gifts, and/or free services</strong>
        from prospective or current vendors, suppliers, or distributors of products or services is prohibited. This includes gifts or payment for room/board, transportation, tickets, or admission to sporting and/or entertainment events. An occasional business meal is permissible. However, it is expected that the Steelcase employee would reciprocate as the opportunity arises.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Accepting supplier provided transportation</strong>
        to visit a supplier should be declined where possible to avoid any appearance of conflict of interest. Exceptions to this might be for safety and security purposes in an unfamiliar region or a pressing business need that makes this necessary, ie. shutting down a production line or missing a critical deadline.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Accepting payment</strong>
        of any nature that may influence Company business decisions.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Misuse of confidential or propriety information</strong>
        to which employees, vendors, consultants, independent contractors, subcontractors, or other third parties have access to by reason of position in the Company. Such dealings could also violate the insider trading laws of the Securities and Exchange Commission, which if violated can result in substantial fines and/or imprisonment. (See the Insider Trading Policy, established by the Legal Department).
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Speculating or dealing</strong>
        in equipment, supplies, materials, or property purchased by the company, or products sold by the Company, for one's personal benefit.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Borrowing money</strong>
        from, or engaging in transactions with, suppliers, customers, or competitors while employed by the Company (other than personal transactions conducted with banks or other financial institutions).
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Performing any activities</strong>
        for remuneration which:
        <ol>
          <li>Involve Company time, equipment, or facilities.</li>
          <li>Involve approaching co-workers to buy products or services.</li>
          <li>Involve services or work performed for any Steelcase entity, joint venture, dealer or customer.</li>
          <li>Involve working on Steelcase or any Steelcase entity related matters through a supplier or vendor (including a temporary employment agency).</li>
          <li>Otherwise conflicts with the employee's obligation to the Company.</li>
        </ol>
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Using or copying materials</strong>
        to promote any organization you own or are involved in without permission from management.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Authorizing the use of company funds</strong>
        whether directly or indirectly, for the purpose of opposing or supporting any government, political party, candidate or committee.
      </li>
      <li>
        <div class="vspace">
          <strong>Using kickbacks and gratuities to obtain business.</strong>
          All activities that in any way are, or appear to be, offered to obtain contracts, subcontracts, or otherwise influence business decisions.
        </div>
        <strong>Note:</strong> The Anti-Kickback Act of 1986 prohibits kickbacks and gratuities involving government contracts or subcontracts. Violations of this act may result in the loss of government business by the company.
      </li>
      <li>
        <div class="vspace">
          <strong>Bribing a foreign government official</strong>,
          authorizing an "agent" of Steelcase to bribe a foreign government official, or possessing knowledge that an "agent" of Steelcase bribed a foreign government official, for the purpose of obtaining or retaining business abroad.
        </div>
        <p>
          <strong>Note:</strong> The Foreign Corrupt Practices Act of 1977 prohibits payment of a bribe by a U.S. Company to any foreign government official for the purpose of obtaining or retaining business. The Act was amended with the International Anti-Bribery and Fair Competition Act of 1998, which included provision of the Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development’s Convention on Combating Bribery of Foreign Public Officials in International Business Transactions. "U.S. Company" is very broadly defined to include U.S. companies, their employees, and agents (defined to include dealers or subcontractors) if Steelcase had knowledge of the payment before it was made by the agent, learns of the agent's payment after the fact but concludes the sale anyway, or had reason to suspect that a payment had been made by the agent and did not investigate before concluding the sale. "Foreign government official" is defined to include political figures, governmental officials, as well as officers, employees, and agents of commercial enterprises that are owned more than 50% by foreign governments, who have discretion over the business in question.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Significant investments</strong>
        in competitors need to be declared. Investments in vendors or companies that Steelcase is doing business with, where you have decision making influence, also need to be declared.
      </li>
    </ul>
  </div>
