  <h4 class="text-center">
    <strong><u>Violence in the Workplace</u></strong>
  </h4>
  <p class="vspace">
    <strong><u>Purpose:</u></strong> To provide a work environment free of violence, to assure all employees have the ability to communicate their concerns over workplace conditions, and to outline the appropriate action for management and employees to take when dealing with individuals who threaten or engage in violent behavior.
  </p>
  <p class="vspace">
    <strong><u>Overview:</u></strong> Steelcase maintains a policy of zero tolerance with regard to workplace violence and will not tolerate any threats, intimidation or acts against other employees, vendors or customers or any deliberate damage of company or personal property Employees may not bring weapons onto company property under any circumstances.
  </p>
  <p class="vspace">
    <strong><u>Violence Prevention:</u></strong> Employees are encouraged to discuss their concerns with supervision before problems escalate to potential violence. An employee who is uncomfortable discussing a concern with his or her supervisor may choose to meet with another member of management, employee relations or human resources. (Reference Human Resources Policy: Open Door).
  </p>
  <p class="vspace">
    The Company also encourages associates who need assistance with personal or emotional problems to contact their employer to see if there are Counseling Services or Employee Assistance Programs available.
  </p>
  <p class="vspace">
    <strong><u>Violent Acts:</u></strong> Any act, deed, threat, or insinuation to commit physical harm to an individual or damage or destruction of company or personal property will constitute a violent act and subject the employee to disciplinary action up to and including termination of employment.
  </p>
  <p class="vspace">
    Steelcase policy of zero tolerance extends to jokes, jests, horseplay and any acts of intimidation. As a result, any threat will be presumed to reflect the employee's intent to physically harm another employee or property and be treated seriously, regardless of whether the employee later claims he or she had no intention of acting on the threat. Steelcase reserves the right to notify the associate's employer for individuals who threaten or engage in workplace violence.
  </p>
  <p class="vspace">
    <strong><u>Possession of a Weapon:</u></strong> Employees may not bring guns, ammunition or any item classified as a weapon under state or local law onto company property unless specifically authorized by the Company. This ban applies to all employees regardless of whether they may have been issued any type of permit to carry a weapon. These items include but are not limited to rifles, shotguns, handguns, and switchblades. lf any employee is uncertain whether an item is considered a weapon, the employee should not bring it onto company property until he or she seeks clarification from protection services. Possession of a weapon on company property will result in disciplinary action up to and including termination of employment.
  </p>
  <p class="vspace">
    <strong><u>lnvestigations:</u></strong> Any act or threat of violence may result in an investigation of the employee's background, criminal history, weapons ownership or police reports. The company reserves the right to search any company property such as work areas, lockers, desks etc. or any personal property an employee brings onto company premises including bags, purses, automob¡les etc.
  </p>
  <p class="vspace">
    <strong><u>Emplovee and Management Responsibilities:</u></strong> All associates working on Steelcase property are responsible for complying with this policy and conducting themselves in a manner free of harassing, intimidating, threatening or violent behavior.
  </p>
  <p class="vspace">
    All employees have an obligation to immediately report any threat or act of violence they observe or are aware of against a coworker, supervisor, visitor or any other individual as well as any threat or action to damage or destroy company or personal property. The potential for injury or loss of life outweighs the obligation to preserve any confidence requested by the employee who issued or witnessed a threat. Employees should report such threats to their supervisor, employee relation's manager, security, or any member of management. Any employee who knowingly fails to report a threat or act of violence is subject to disciplinary act¡on up to and including termination of employment.
  </p>
  <p class="vspace">
    Employee reports will be held in confidence to the maximum possible extent. Steelcase will not condone any form of retaliation aga¡nst any employee for making a report under this policy.
  </p>
