  <p>
    <strong><em>Overview</em></strong>
  </p>
  <p class="vspace">
    Steelcase policy is to prevent substance abuse and to deal appropriately with abuse problems which arise. The contractor employee’s agency administers drug tests to all employment candidates if the plan is for them to work onsite at a designated Steelcase facility.
  </p>
  <p>
    Steelcase understands that persons who abuse drugs and alcohol are involved in incidents and are injured more frequently than non-drug users. As part of our effort to maintain a safe workplace, Steelcase may require testing as follows:
  </p>
  <div class="wrapper-inner vspace">
    <ul>
      <li>Upon a contractor’s involvement in an incident, the contractor receives a drug and alcohol test.</li>
      <li>
        Upon initial offer of employment or return from any leave of 30 or more days, the contractor receives a drug test.
      </li>
      <li>
        A health and safety professional may ask a contract employee to submit to a test when the contractor exhibits symptoms of being under the influence of drugs or alcohol.
      </li>
    </ul>
  </div>
  <p class="vspace">
    Any confirmed positive test will result in corrective and/or disciplinary action at the discretion of the company as described in this policy.
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong><em>Substance Abuse</em></strong>
  </p>
  <p class="vspace">
    Company policy prohibits contracted employees from possessing, using or being under the influence of a non-prescribed controlled substance or alcohol during work hours and/or on company property. "Under the influence" is defined as the presence of controlled substances or alcohol in a person's system. "Company property" includes, but is not limited to, any company facility, employer or contractor parking lots, company owned or leased vehicles and other equipment. Contract employees found selling or transferring any controlled substances on or off Steelcase property, based on reasonably objective evidence of such activity (regardless of whether an arrest and/or conviction for such activity occurs), or arrested and convicted for selling controlled substances, or any lesser included offense resulting from such activity (including, e.g., intent to distribute, possession, delivery, or use) are subject to suspension, possibly leading to discharge.
  </p>
  <p class="vspace">
    The contracted employee can refuse counseling, can refuse to submit to a substance abuse test, and can refuse permission to be searched or have his or her personal property searched. Such refusal, however, will result in discipline such as immediate suspension and possible termination of employment.
  </p>
  <p class="vspace">
    In addition, no contracted employee is to work at any time while using any medication that could impair the contracted employee's safe and effective job performance. This policy applies to both prescription and over-the-counter medications.
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong><em>Definitions</em></strong>
  </p>
  <p class="vspace">
    For purposes of this policy, an incident is any event that threatens or causes personal injury or property damage, reckless or unsafe behavior on the job, or other circumstances giving reason to suspect a violation of this policy.
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong><em>A positive test for alcohol is:</em></strong>
  </p>
  <p>A positive test for alcohol is:</p>
  <p>A blood or urine alcohol level of 0.05 dl or greater</p>
  <p class="vspace">
    <strong><em>A blood or urine alcohol level of 0.05 dl or greater</em></strong>
  </p>
