  <div class="vspace text-center">
    <strong>It's all about doing what's right.</strong>
  </div>
  <p class="vspace">
    As a Steelcase contract employee or resident vendor, you are expected to follow our corporate policies, practices, guides, handbooks, and the laws and regulations governing these areas where Steelcase Inc. does business. Being a global company means that the way we do business must recognize and comply with the laws and regulations of international commerce. It requires understanding the laws and culture of all countries in which we are located or serve customers.
  </p>
  <p class="vspace">
    And as a part of a law called The Sarbanes-Oxley act of 2002, Steelcase is required to train all employees on our legal and ethical guidelines. It's all about doing what's right.
  </p>
  <p class="vspace">
    These guidelines are called our Global Business Standards. They spell out what employees and vendors, including you, should do when confronted with serious or questionable situations at work, including harassment, theft, or misuse of company property. Obviously, some of these situations have legal and moral consequences, not just for the individual but for the company as a whole.
  </p>
  <p class="vspace">
    So, it's our responsibility to act lawfully, ethically, fairly, and in a manner that sustains healthy business relationships and instills loyalty with each other, our customers, our shareholders, and our business partners, all within the confines of the law. We want you to know how to handle potentially serious situations and who to go to with questions or concerns.
  </p>
  <p class="vspace">
    This document serves as your training on Steelcase's Global Business Standards. Please review the examples below so you'll know what to do if you ever witness or become involved in one of these situations.
  </p>
  <div class="wrapper-inner vspace">
    <ul>
      <li>
        <strong>Treat people with dignity and respect.</strong> The company will not tolerate discriminatory behaviors or practices within any of our work environments. Our people have the right to work in an atmosphere that is free from intimidation, threats, hostility, violence, harassment, or disruptions to work performance. You are expected to promptly report discriminatory or harassment behaviors to Human Resources or your supervisor.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Provide a safe and healthy environment.</strong> Report all accidents, injuries, unsafe practices or conditions to your supervisor. All associates are expected to observe safety and health rules.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Maintain accurate business records.</strong> You are expected to provide accurate and adequate information when disclosing financial information on these records. You are expected to follow all statutory and regulatory requirements, and obey all applicable rules of federal, state, and local governments.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Disclosing information about Steel case Inc. Operations.</strong> All requests for financial data or information regarding the operations of Steelcase Inc. should be directed to the Investor Relations department.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Responding to media requests or making public statements.</strong> Requests for information from the media should be cleared through the Public Relations/Corporate Communications Department.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Avoid conflicts of interest.</strong> Employees must not allow personal considerations or relationships to influence their business-related decisions. Examples of conflicts of interest include outside financial interests; doing business with relatives; accepting or giving business gifts, money, or hospitality.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Avoid gambling/loan activity.</strong> Gambling is not permitted on Steelcase time or property. While on company property, any exchange of money for leagues, pool, or games is gambling, even if you are on a break or lunch.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Firearms and other items classified as weapons are not permitted on company property.</strong> Steelcase is responsible for maintaining a safe work environment, even if the employee has a license to carry a weapon. If you become aware of weapons present on Steelcase property, you should contact your supervisor, Protection Services, or HR immediately.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Protect the environment.</strong> The goal is to be proactive and continually incorporate environmental, health and safety considerations into our products, activities, and services.
      </li>
    </ul>
  </div>
  <p class="vspace">
    You are expected to report suspicious activities or known violations of our Global Business Standards. The first place to go to is your supervisor or HR. But if you can't resolve a situation that way, call the North American Toll Free Integrity Line at 1-800-437-6167 or access the Integrity Line Website at <a href="https://www.compliance-helpline.com/welcomePageSteelcase.jsp">https://www.compliance-helpline.com/welcomePageSteelcase.jsp</a>. All inquires are confidential, and Steelcase policy protects employees from being threatened or punished in any way for reporting suspected violations. For a complete copy of the Global Business Standard policy, see your supervisor or agency contract manager.
  </p>
